% start of ramble
%
% if you want to know what was on my mind when I wrote "order" or "partial order"
%
% there is a natural order in a merkle tree for leaves (their index at level 0), same for a list of anything (the order of appearance in the list) and as we incrementally build a large collection of lists and trees, if we tie them together enough, what we get is an appearance order for each and every hash ever included in AT
%
% what we have with "hash(item) -> $FOO" is a random oracle and what we build with AT is an history of queries observers claims to have made to the oracle, with claims made on the order in which these queries have been made (X comes before Y)
%
% this is a partial order
%
% the trust contract is that tlogs ensure that this partial order is always the same and is never modified, while the end-user is the one trying to reproduce the queries
%
% by hashing an item in its possession, an end-user verify the claim that an observer made some time ago, that "hash(item) -> $FOO", and then the end-user rely on the fact that the partial order of all queries ever recorded, is immutable and never changed
%
% if we insert in that partial order, entries for which an explicit link/anchor to real time from the real world have been verified (like a trusted timestamp, or witness signature, etc) we obtain a way, for any old query found in the history, to have a [before, after] window of "first time recorded"
%
% this is revelant as the overall log/immense pile of "lists of files" grows and some will inevitably decay/be lost/be corrupted, we **will** lose confidence in most individual older links to real time, but the partial ordering and the knowledge that "it was validated as OK when first included" helps us maintain some confidence
%
% end of ramble



