% start of ramble
%
% one thing that is cheap to do when doing timestamping is the "linking":
%    - when building lists of files, then adding trusted timestamps to them...
%      ...we include previous lists of files, in the list, to timestamp them again
%
% in earlier revisions of me describing AT, I was talking about "horizontal inclusion" (but I stopped mentioning it to not make it too terminology-heavy, heh)
%
% in short, it's nice to have a "vertical inclusion" with a well-formed tree linking everyone to the same head of a limited set of global transparency logs, it is good for efficiency and automation, the model is clear, easy to work with, etc
%
% but trees burns down
%
% it's cheap to have "horizontal inclusion" (new documents/lists includes previous ones) like observers doing co-inclusion with the tlog or the observer including a hash of its most recent document, but validating the "tangled mess" makes everything harder and confusing
%
% the idea here is to use the tlogs to force everyone into doing horizontal inclusion, validating it, so we know it's here, even if in production we don't use it all the time
%
% but when trees burn down, we get "holes" with missing leaves, lost identities, a messy patchwork of things, but it's not that catastrophic: we can take what's left, archive it, start with a clean state and continue
%
% in the meanwhile, if users from the far future, finds a very interesting item/file in the tangled mess, it will be up to them to build the very complex proof argument to show that item comes from the past, providing them a "backup plan" for burned trees
%
% we get the cake (in the present days, 99.9% of the time, it's simple and efficient)
% and a backup of the cake (future day, 0.1% bad failure mode, complex slow recovery)
%
% end of ramble



