the exact usage model is described in more details below, but the "first interesting thing" we can do with archive transparency, is to include for each existing "digital bundle of archival items" that already exist, a document describing that bundle

this is a niche application, but it solves the trust problem of distributing archives

this usage model is the simpler one & nicer one to implement:
  - user gets the document with the files (like user get x509 cert when get website)
  - user verify the inclusion the document in global tlog (like cert. inclusion in CT)
  - then user check that individual items are in document (like subdomain in cert. SAN)


searching an individual item in the whole archive transparency, is the the same problem as searching a domain name in the whole certificate transparency, this costs resources

however to maximize adoption, we do a bit of extra work (include more metadata than needed) to enable these secondary use cases, as the more useful we are, the more likely we are to see adoption by the archives (where +1% storage is cheap, but good up-to-date maintained software is very rare and very expensive to them)


% start of ramble
%
% the #1 usage model I first want to target, is to include the documents / lists of files in the "bundles of files" that exists for the web, also called "WARC"/"WACZ" (for "Web ARChives" or "Web Archive Collection Zipped") which are many files concatenated
%
% in #1 the observer document / the "lists of files" is distributed along the "bundle of files" it authenticates, so the user is able to check offline the inclusion of a specific file from the bundle, inside the document, then verify the inclusion of the document inside the centralized global log
%
% this is useful because often WARC/WACZ files are 50Mo-50Go and users load them in local browsers, then want to be able to browse locally this "snapshot of the past" while being sure that yes, it comes from the past (this is done for now with bad checksums like sha1/md5 and naked rfc3161 trusted timestamps, which is ok but meh)
%
%
% the #2 usage model is when users have a single file, attached to nothing, and this adds an expensive step "finding where the file has been recorded" which requires a search inside a potentially vast amount of documents
%
% the question for #2 becomes "who spends the resources"
%
% one thing useful to answer this question, is that in the current draft:
%    - the documents / "lists of files" are also merkle trees in a trenchcoat
%
% the data model in archive transparency (currently) is:
%  - digests & metadata are serialized inside "records" (a record describes "a thing")
%  - each observer number its records, starting from 0 (which is secretly a leaf index)
%  - documents are records concatenated (e.g. record0.bytes || record1.bytes || ...)
%
% the complete collection of the documents produced by an observer, concatenated, is equivalent to all the leaves of a small tree, local to the given observer, and given proper precautions, efficient proofs can be generated for a single item
%
% in #1 the workflow of proof looks like:
%  1. grep "$hash" ./document.txt
%  2. recordA := record[hash(document.txt), metadata] *this is canon and done offline
%  3. go to API to get inclusion proof of $recordA
%  4. verify proof [hash(0x0 || recordA), ... inclusion path ...]
%
% this requires "document" distributed together with the items
%
% in #2 what can be done by $someone is:
%  1. go to API to get "$hash" -> document.txt (user downloads the document)
%                              +  inclusion proof of $recordA in global tlog
%  2. grep "$hash" ./document.txt
%  3. recomputes $recordA and verify its inclusion proof in global tlog
%
% this requires $someone resolving the hash and spending bandwidth to send the document
% (and documents for large bundles can be dozens of megabytes, which is expensive)
%
% if $someone wants to spend more CPU but less bandwidth, we can do a #3 as follows:
%  1. go to API to get "$hash" -> recordB
%                              + inclusion proof of $recordB in document.txt
%                              + recordA
%                              + inclusion proof of $recordA in global tlog
%  2. echo "$recordB" | grep "$hash"
%  3. verify inclusion proof in document.txt **using metadata found in recordA**
%  4. verify inclusion proof of recordA in global tlog
%
% this #3 costs computation to $someone but user can get a proof for a single item
% (and some of my confusion around $POLICY is defining how to support #2 and #3)
%
% however, initial goal is to support #1 only, which is very close to "regular tlog"
%
% the biggest use case for archive transparency is #1 because large archives want to enable anyone to get their "bundles" and redistribute them, and now doing this is hard because of a trust problem (and current attempts to distribute that is blockchain only)
%
% currently, to distribute trust:
%  - $big_archive spends lots of effort to adopt $decentralized_technology
%  - $decentralized_technology makes complex arguments to ensure $trust
%
% doing transparency is a sane model:
%  - $big_archive generates its own text documents and store them with existing bundles
%  - user go "haha downloaded a big bundle of files hoho" with regular HTTP
%  - proofs and verification is done without help of $big_archive
%
% this enable anyone to start redistributing the bundles, and if barrier to entry is low enough for $big_archive to enroll (as easy as certbot) anyone can profit
%
% the #2 and #3 are just nice to have to drive adoption by adding value to the system
%
% end of ramble

